d harmonies and big sing‑along choruses, which are positives. However, it emphasizes a slightly ragged, forward lead vocal, layered electric‑guitar attack, organ accents and a vintage, guitar‑driven classic‑rock AOR sequencing. That points to a rougher, more guitar‑centric, possibly male‑ensemble or ragged vocal aesthetic rather than the polished, female midrange, piano/guitar singer‑centered anthology I prefer.\n3) Why I choose CD 2 and reject CD 1:\n- CD 2 aligns with multiple specific, stated preferences: it preserves dynamics and sparkle (so it won’t flatten vocals or dynamics), offers spacious, vocal‑forward mixes (my top priority), and highlights tight multi‑part harmonies and piano/guitar arrangements — all core aspects I mentioned wanting. The explicit singer‑centered sequencing featuring Stevie Nicks/Christine McVie signals warm female midrange leads and an album‑scale listening experience that rewards front‑to‑back plays, matching my desire for tactile sequencing and singer‑centered presentation.\n- CD 1, while appealing in its own right (dynamic, sing‑along choruses, vintage guitar energy), skews toward a ragged, guitar‑forward AOR vibe. That makes it less ideal: the “slightly ragged lead vocals” and aggressive electric‑guitar focus reduce the intimacy and midrange female vocal presence I prize, and the classic‑rock sequencing suggests less of the singer‑centered, piano/guitar‑forward album narrative I prefer. Although CD 1 preserves dynamics and has rich harmonies, its tonal and stylistic emphasis risks being male/ensemble or overly raw when I want warm, polished female midrange leads with cinematic immediacy.\n- Because my priorities place vocal presence (warm female midrange), clean/punchy sparkling mastering, piano/guitar arrangements, tight harmonies, and front‑to‑back singer‑centered sequencing above a raw classic‑rock AOR presentation, CD 2 is the clear match and CD 1 is the one I reject.'. \n\n However, upon actually listening to these two CDs, yo