The recommender system made unsuitable recommendation. 
 Its reasons are as follows: Preferences and dislikes (from my self‑introduction): I prefer tactile, expressive guitar attack and tight, driving drums/bass; gravelly/roomy lead vocals with breath and consonant detail; analogue warmth, low compression and transient‑preserving mastering with ample headroom; conservative compression that preserves punchy transients and midrange warmth; transparent multi‑part harmonies and restrained overdubs; piano/acoustic parts that support rather than crowd the singer; and airy, dynamic mastering with clear separation and tactile LP flow. I dislike heavy limiting or loud matched masters that flatten dynamics; over‑polished AOR sheen or sterile single‑track gloss; excessive reverb that obscures lyrics; bass‑forward radio mastering that sacrifices midrange focus; scattershot sequencing; and mixes that bury the musical focal point.
Evaluation and choice rationale:
- The Boston AOR mix directly addresses the core of what I prize: “big layered overdriven electrics” gives the tactile, expressive guitar attack I want; “tight rhythmic pockets” and “punchy propulsive low end” satisfy my need for driving drums/bass and rhythmic focus without suggesting bass‑forward radio compression. Crucially, the description calls out “upfront tactile midrange vocals that retain breath and consonant detail,” which aligns with my preference for vocals that have presence and intelligibility rather than being overly dry or buried.
- The Boston disc also notes “tasteful multi‑tracked harmonies,” “analog tape warmth,” and a “restrained remaster preserving headroom and transient snap.” Those attributes match several of my technical requirements: transparent harmonies, analogue color, low compression, and transient‑preserving mastering with ample headroom. The presence of natural/roomy reverb is stated but paired with retained consonant detail, so it does not appear to be the kind of excessive reverb that would obscure lyrics — it reads as natural space rather than a wash that hides the focal point.
- By contrast, the Carly Simon “Reflections” set is intimate and vocal‑forward with close‑mic, dry midrange leads and minimal reverb. While that satisfies my taste for preserved tape warmth and micro‑dynamics, it misses other major preferences: it emphasizes close, dry vocal presentation and concise 2–3 minute pop arrangements rather than the roomy, guitar/driven, rhythmically propulsive sound I described as my strongest likes. I specifically called out a liking for tactile guitar attack and tight, driving drums/bass; Carly Simon’s hits are melody‑first, acoustic/arrangement focused and unlikely to deliver the aggressive guitar and rhythmic punch I seek. Also, the very close, dry lead vocal aesthetic conflicts with my stated preference for a roomy, slightly reverberant lead that still retains breath and consonant detail — I prefer presence with space rather than an intimate close‑mic sound as the defining character.
- I also must weigh my dislike of “over‑polished AOR sheen.” Although the Boston disc is AOR-era in origin, its description emphasizes “authentic 1976” mix, analog tape warmth, tasteful harmonies and a “restrained remaster preserving headroom and transient snap.” That makes it more of an authentic, dynamic period mix than a modern, over‑polished loudness‑driven treatment, so it does not trigger the over‑polished/flattened master dislike. In short, Boston provides the energetic guitar/drum/bass focus, multi‑tracked harmonies, analogue warmth and headroom I want, while Carly Simon, despite being well‑mastered and intimate, does not meet my stronger needs for tactile electric guitar and rhythmic drive.
Therefore I select the Authentic 1976 Boston AOR mix as the closer match to my stated sonic and mastering preferences and reject Reflections—Carly Simon hits because its close‑mic, dry, melody‑first intimacy lacks the guitar/drums/bass energy and roomy vocal presence I prioritized.

